{"title_page": "Lac La Ronge Indian Band", "text_new": "{{Infobox First Nation\n| band_name             = Lac La Ronge Indian Band\n| band_number           = 353\n| endonym               = \n| image                 = \n| caption               = \n| map                   = \n| map_caption           = \n| people                = [[Woodland Cree]]\n| treaty                = [[Treaty 6]]\n| headquarters          = [[La Ronge]]\n| province              = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| main_reserve          = \n| reserve               = \n*[[Little Red River 106C]]\n*[[Little Red River 106D]]\n*[[Lac la Ronge 156]]\n*[[Potato River 156A]]\n*[[Kitsakie 156B]]\n*[[Sucker River 156C]]\n*[[Stanley 157]]\n*[[Stanley 157A]]\n*[[Old Fort 157B]]\n*[[Four Portages 157C]]\n*[[Fox Point 157D]]\n*[[Fox Point 157E]]\n*[[Little Hills 158]]\n*[[Little Hills 158A]]\n*[[Little Hills 158B]]\n*[[Morin Lake 217]]\n*[[Bittern Lake 218]]\n*[[Grandmother's Bay 219]]\n*[[Kiskinwuhumatowin]]\n| area                  = 433.052\n| pop_year              = 2019\n| on_reserve            = 6818\n| on_other_land         = 179\n| off_reserve           = 4180\n| total_pop             = \n| chief                 = Tammy Miriam Cook-Searson\n| council               = \n| tribal_council        = [[Prince Albert Grand Council]]\n| website               = [http://llrib.com/ llrib.com]\n| footnotes             = <ref>{{Cite web|title=First Nation Detail|website=Indigenous and Northern Affairs Canada|publisher=Government of Canada|access-date=September 10, 2019|url=http://fnp-ppn.aandc-aadnc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNMain.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=353&lang=eng}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Lac La Ronge Indian Band''' is the largest [[Cree]] [[First Nations|First Nation]] [[band government]] in [[La Ronge]], [[Saskatchewan]], and one of the 10 largest in Canada, with a 2016 population of 10,408. Its location is in north-central Saskatchewan. They are a [[Woodland Cree]] First Nation. \n\n[[Indian reserve|Reserve]] lands extend from rich farmlands in central Saskatchewan, north through the boreal forest to the Churchill River and beyond. The central administration office is located in La Ronge, 241&nbsp;km north of Prince Albert, on the edge of the Pre-Cambrian Shield.\n\n==History==\n'''La Ronge & Stanley Mission Band of Woods Cree Indians''' became a signatory to the [[Treaty 6]] on February 11, 1889, signed by Chief James Roberts. In 1900 Peter Ballantyne was allowed to separate from the La Ronge and Stanley Mission Band to form the Peter Ballantyne Band of Cree Indians, the predecessor to the [[Peter Ballantyne Cree Nation]]. In 1910, the La Ronge & Stanley Mission Band split into two entities: '''Amos Charles Band of Cree Indians'''  (located in Stanley Mission) and the '''James Roberts Band of Cree Indians''' (located in La Ronge).  In 1950, the two Bands amalgamated and became the '''Lac La Ronge Indian Band''', the current legal name.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.llrib.ca/history.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-09-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005173352/http://www.llrib.ca/history.php |archivedate=2009-10-05 }} History</ref>\n\n==Reserves and Communities==\nLac La Ronge Indian Band's land-base consists of 18 [[Indian reserve]]s, some containing one of six communities:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pse5-esd5.ainc-inac.gc.ca/FNP/Main/Search/FNReserves.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=353&lang=eng |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305171140/http://pse5-esd5.ainc-inac.gc.ca/FNP/Main/Search/FNReserves.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=353&lang=eng |archivedate=2016-03-05 }}</ref>\n\n* Bittern Lake 218\u2014{{convert|6886|ha|acre}}\n* [[Four Portages 157C]]\u2014{{convert|0.20|ha|acre}}\n* Fox Point 157D\u2014{{convert|56.70|ha|acre}}\n* Fox Point 157E\u2014{{convert|4.20|ha|acre}}\n* [[Grandmother's Bay 219]]\u2014{{convert|4488.90|ha|acre}}\u2014containing the community of Grandmother's Bay\n* Kitsakie 156B\u2014{{convert|74|ha|acre}}\n* [[Lac La Ronge 156]]\u2014{{convert|605.40|ha|acre}}\u2014containing the community of [[La Ronge, Saskatchewan|La Ronge]]\n* [[Little Hills 158]]\u2014{{convert|517.20|ha|acre}}\n* Little Hills 158A\u2014{{convert|38.30|ha|acre}}\n* [[Little Hills 158B]]\u2014{{convert|131.20|ha|acre}}\n* [[Little Red River 106C]]\u2014{{convert|12939.30|ha|acre}}\u2014containing the community of Little Red River\n** originally {{convert|12302.44|ha|acre}}\n** in 1935, additional {{convert|650.69|ha|acre}} reserved\n* Little Red River 106D\u2014{{convert|2590|ha|acre}}\n* [[Morin Lake 217]]\u2014{{convert|14146.10|ha|acre}}\u2014containing the community of Hall Lake\n** originally {{convert|13208.94|ha|acre}}\n** in 1973, additional {{convert|936.85|ha|acre}} reserved\n* Old Fort 157B\u2014{{convert|5.40|ha|acre}}\n* [[Potato River 156A]]\u2014{{convert|409.50|ha|acre}}\n* [[Stanley 157]]\u2014{{convert|251.30|ha|acre}}\u2014containing the community of [[Stanley Mission, Saskatchewan|Stanley Mission]]\n* Stanley 157A\u2014{{convert|3.80|ha|acre}}\n* [[Sucker River 156C]]\u2014{{convert|154.80|ha|acre}}\u2014containing the community of Sucker River\n\nThe communities of Stanley Mission and Grandmother's Bay are self-administered. This arrangement ensures that these communities have more control over their services and programs.<ref>[http://llrib.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=51&Itemid=29 About Us<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Governance ==\nThe First Nation elects their Council under the Custom Electoral System, consisting of a chief and 12 councillors. The current Council consists of Chief Tammy Cook-Searson and Councillors Leon Charles, Linda Charles, McIvor Eninew, Lawrence Halkett, Irwin Hennie, Larry McKenzie, Keith Mirasty, Ann Ratt, Bernice Roberts, John Roberts, Sam Roberts, and Cheryline Venne. They were elected for a three-year term beginning April 1, 2014 and ending March 31, 2017. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://pse5-esd5.ainc-inac.gc.ca/FNP/Main/Search/FNGovernance.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=353&lang=eng |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305165303/http://pse5-esd5.ainc-inac.gc.ca/FNP/Main/Search/FNGovernance.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=353&lang=eng |archivedate=2016-03-05 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of First Nations peoples]]\n* [[Federation of Sovereign Indigenous Nations]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.llrib.org/ Lac La Ronge Indian Band]\n\n{{FirstNations-stub}}\n\n{{Numbertreaty|treaty=6}}\n{{First Nations in Saskatchewan}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations governments in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Cree governments]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox First Nation\n| band_name             = Lac La Ronge Indian Band\n| band_number           = 353\n| endonym               = \n| image                 = \n| caption               = \n| map                   = \n| map_caption           = \n| people                = [[Woodland Cree]]\n| treaty                = [[Treaty 6]]\n| headquarters          = [[La Ronge]]\n| province              = [[Saskatchewan]]\n| main_reserve          = \n| reserve               = \n*[[Little Red River 106C]]\n*[[Little Red River 106D]]\n*[[Lac la Ronge 156]]\n*[[Potato River 156A]]\n*[[Kitsakie 156B]]\n*[[Sucker River 156C]]\n*[[Stanley 157]]\n*[[Stanley 157A]]\n*[[Old Fort 157B]]\n*[[Four Portages 157C]]\n*[[Fox Point 157D]]\n*[[Fox Point 157E]]\n*[[Little Hills 158]]\n*[[Little Hills 158A]]\n*[[Little Hills 158B]]\n*[[Morin Lake 217]]\n*[[Bittern Lake 218]]\n*[[Grandmother's Bay 219]]\n*[[Kiskinwuhumatowin]]\n| area                  = 433.052\n| pop_year              = 2019\n| on_reserve            = 6818\n| on_other_land         = 179\n| off_reserve           = 4180\n| total_pop             = \n| chief                 = Tammy Miriam Cook-Searson\n| council               = \n| tribal_council        = [[Prince Albert Grand Council]]\n| website               = [http://llrib.