 korona orsz\u00e1gai t\u00f6rt\u00e9net\u00e9nek, f\u00f6ldrajzi, k\u00e9pz\u0151m\u0171v\u00e9szeti, n\u00e9prajzi, had\u00fcgyi \u00e9s term\u00e9szeti viszonyainak, k\u00f6zm\u0171vel\u0151d\u00e9si \u00e9s k\u00f6zgazdas\u00e1gi \u00e1llapot\u00e1nak encziklop\u00e9di\u00e1ja''. Szerk. Borovszky Samu. Budapest: Orsz\u00e1gos Monografia T\u00e1rsas\u00e1g. 1908.\n* Magyar n\u00e9prajzi lexikon\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Szabolcs-Szatm\u00e1r-Bereg County|Porcsalma]]\n\n{{Szabolcs-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Porcsalma"}
{"title_page": "Giygas", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n|name = Giygas\n|color = #A00010\n|image =File:Giygas.png\n|caption = Giygas as he appears in ''[[EarthBound]]''\n|series = [[EarthBound (series)|EarthBound]]\n|species = [[Extraterrestrial Life|Alien]]\n|first = ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]'' (1989)\n|last = ''[[EarthBound]]'' (1994)\n|creator = [[Shigesato Itoi]]\n}}\n'''Giygas''', also known as '''Giegue''', and {{nihongo|'''Gyiyg'''|\u30ae\u30fc\u30b0|G\u012bgu}} in Japan, is a [[Extraterrestrials in fiction|fictional alien character]] in the ''[[EarthBound (series)|EarthBound]]'' video game series by [[Nintendo]], created by [[Shigesato Itoi]]. The character serves as the main antagonist of ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]'' and its sequel, ''[[EarthBound]]''. He invades Earth in an attempt to wipe out humanity in ''Mother'', and returns in ''EarthBound'' where he conquers the world and sends his forces into the past to ensure that protagonist [[Ness (EarthBound)|Ness]] could not defeat him. The battle against Giygas, which depicts him in turmoil, drew inspiration from a Japanese film which traumatized Itoi as a child. He has received positive reception with critics referring to his battle as one of the creepiest and most difficult in video games. He has been the subject of analysis and speculation, with an [[urban legend]] being spread about the final battle with him in ''EarthBound'' being a representation of an abortion, which staff denied.\n\n==Concept and creation==\nGiygas was designed and written by the creator of the [[EarthBound (series)|''EarthBound'' series]],  [[Shigesato Itoi]], and debuted in the original ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]''. He is known as Gyiyg in Japanese and Giegue in the canceled English localization. In an interview on his website, Itoi describes how his inspiration for the final battle with Giygas in ''EarthBound'' resulted from a traumatic childhood event where he accidentally viewed the wrong movie at a theater, a [[Shintoho]] film entitled ''[[Kenpei to barabara shibijin]]''. The film featured a murder scene near a river that Itoi mistook for a rape scene which affected him so much that his parents began to worry about his well-being. Years later, Itoi integrated the experience into Giygas' dialogue for the final battle. Itoi described Giygas as something that people cannot make sense of, but also as a living being who deserves love. He described the film scene as a combination of atrocity and eroticism, and that is what his lines are in the end. While designing this battle, Itoi spoke all of the text out loud while another staff member, Matchan Miura, wrote it down. He spoke each [[hiragana]] character one by one because he found it scarier.<ref name = \"Itoi interview\">{{cite interview |first=Itoi |last=Shigesato |url=http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/07.html |title=[Interview with Shigesato Itoi] |work=1101.com |date=April 24, 2003 |language=Japanese |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6QrkuC8iK?url=http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/07.html |archive-date=July 6, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"1101.com\">{{cite interview |last=Shigesato |first=Itoi |title=[Interview with Shigesato Itoi] |url=http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/03.html |language=Japanese |work=1101.com |date=April 18, 2003 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330065450/http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/03.html |archive-date=March 30, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> There has been a misunderstanding regarding the influence of the film on Giygas, with some believing that imagery, dialogue, or audio from that film were used here, when the only thing Itoi took from it was the ability to \"manipulate an audience's emotional state.\"<ref name=\"lol\"/> Music composer [[Hirokazu Tanaka]] described Giygas as the \"embodiment of evil\". As a result, he composed the music in a certain way based on the player's proximity to him. For example, in battles where Ness and company encounter someone or something under Giygas' control, the music and sound effects reflect this.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Hirokazu |first=Tanaka |interviewer=Baiyon |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/26447/Interview_PixelJunk_Edens_Baiyon_Vs_Metroids_Hip_Tanaka.php |title=Interview: ''PixelJunk Eden''{{'}}s Baiyon Vs. ''Metroid''{{'}}s Hip Tanaka |work=[[Gamasutra]] |date=December 14, 2009 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018185959/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/26447/Interview_PixelJunk_Edens_Baiyon_Vs_Metroids_Hip_Tanaka.php |archive-date=October 18, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBefore the release of ''EarthBound'', the localization team had at one point considered localizing Giygas as his original name Giegue or Geek.\"<ref name=\"lol\">{{cite web |url=https://legendsoflocalization.com/earthbound/giygas/ |title=Giygas |work=Legends of Localization |last=Mandelin |first=Clyde |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901012650/https://legendsoflocalization.com/earthbound/giygas/ |archive-date=September 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was speculated that the change from Giegue to Giygas was due to a change in localization staff.<ref name=\"lol\"/> An [[urban legend]] exists that suggests that the final battle with Giygas in ''EarthBound'' was an \"alien [[abortion]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top 7... Creepiest gaming urban legends |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-7-creepiest-gaming-urban-legends/ |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |last=Cooper |first=Hollander |date=November 2, 2012 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221092216/http://gamesradar.com/top-7-creepiest-gaming-urban-legends/ |archive-date=February 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Marcus Lindblom]], a member of the English localization team, acknowledged the urban legend, noting that he appreciated the speculation, but debunked the idea as an official interpretation.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Man Who Wrote Earthbound |url=http://kotaku.com/the-man-who-wrote-earthbound-1188669175 |work=[[Kotaku]] |last=Schreier |first=Jason |date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MtORg2Ew?url=http://kotaku.com/the-man-who-wrote-earthbound-1188669175 |archive-date=January 25, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\nGiygas appears in the [[Family Computer]] video game, ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]''.<ref name=\"mother\"/> Giygas was raised by Maria, a woman abducted along with her husband George by Giygas' alien race from Earth in the early 1900s. George studied the aliens' PSI powers without permission and escaped back to Earth. Once he matured, Giygas was tasked by his people to make sure that PSI never spread onto Earth. However, Giygas did not want to betray those who raised him, particularly Maria. In the end, he forced himself to detach from Maria and began preparations for the aliens' invasion. Eighty years later, strange things start happening on Earth. These events are eventually revealed to be the work of Giygas. Maria, now a Queen in a magical world called Magicant, explains everything to the protagonists of ''Mother'' after her memories are restored. When the protagonists encounter Giygas, he explains his motives to them while attacking them with his PSI power. Maria urges protagonist Ninten to sing, which weakens Giygas. Ninten, Ana, and Lloyd sing together, forcing Giygas to surrender and flee.\n\nGiygas also appears in the [[Super NES]] sequel ''[[EarthBound]]''.<ref name=\"1up\"/> Giygas is an unseen villain for most of the story, although he possesses humans, animals, and objects who unknowingly do his bidding. According to a character from the future named Buzz Buzz, Giygas destroys the universe ten years in the future. One of his key minions is Pokey Minch, a former friend of protagonist [[Ness (EarthBound)|Ness]]. At first, Dr. Andonuts (the father of playable character [[Jeff Andonuts|Jeff]]) believes that Giygas is residing deep within the Earth, and transports himself and the party there using a machine called the Phase Distorter. When they arrive, they find that Giygas is attacking from that exact location, but from innumerable years in the past. The only way the protagonists can get to Giygas' time period is to alter the Phase Distorter to transport them back in time. When the group finally reaches Giygas, he initially resembles Ness while in the device called the \"Devil's Machine.\" Pokey eventually turns the Devil's Machine off, thereby destroying Giygas' body and mind by releasing his power and driving him mad. At this point, Giygas' words are nondescript and nonsensical. Giygas is eventually destroyed by Paula, who prays to the protagonists' friends and family for help. Her praying eventually reaches the player, and the combined prayers do enough damage to Giygas, killing him.\n\n==Reception==\nSince appearing in ''[[EarthBound]]'', Giygas has received largely positive reception. His role and design was regarded as contrasting with the otherwise lighthearted tone of the rest of ''EarthBound''{{'}}s story by Brittany Vincent for ''[[G4TV]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top Unintentionally Terrifying Games Of All Time |url=http://www.g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/717787/top-unintentionally-terrifying-games-of-all-time/ |work=[[G4TV]] |last=Vincent |first=Brittany |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605122659/http://www.g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/717787/top-unintentionally-terrifying-games-of-all-time/ |archive-date=June 5, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cassandra Ramos for ''RPGamer'' identified him as one of her favorite villains, while ''[[1UP.com]]'' staff listed the battle with Giygas as one of the 25 best boss battles, citing the audio and imagery of Giygas as well as the final portion of the battle.<ref name=\"1up\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=4&cId=3173294 |author=1UP Staff |title=25 of the Most Badass Boss Fights of All Time |work=[[1UP.com]] |date=March 17, 2009 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205030310/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=4&cId=3173294 |archive-date=December 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"rpgamer\"/> Jeremy Parish for ''1UP.com'' used the battle as an example of how games subvert expectations, where the protagonists employ prayer instead of their most powerful attacks to win.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jeremy |last=Parish |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3149536 |title=Retronauts 5: Earthbound |work=[[1UP.com]] |date=April 13, 2006 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614121824/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3149536 |archive-date=June 14, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[IGN]]'' staff included the battle with Giygas in their list of the 10 most cinematic video game moments.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 Cinematic Moments in Games |url=http://me.ign.com/en/feature/15877/10-cinematic-moments-in-games |work=[[IGN]] |date=March 10, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007081019/http://me.ign.com/en/feature/15877/10-cinematic-moments-in-games |archive-date=October 7, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''NGamer UK''  staff listed Giygas as one of the most iconic boss encounters in Nintendo history, stating that the defining moment was his design and the method of defeating him.<ref>{{cite web |author=NGamer UK |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendos-most-iconic-boss-encounters/?page=2 |title=Nintendo's most iconic Boss encounters |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=May 11, 2010 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602201131/http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendos-most-iconic-boss-encounters/?page=2 |archive-date=June 2, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' staff named him one of the best video game antagonists, finding him creepy and a more imposing villain than [[Kefka Palazzo]] from ''[[Final Fantasy VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/|title=100 best villains in video games |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=May 17, 2013|accessdate=June 21, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130624192529/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/|archive-date=June 24, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Not Final Fantasy |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/not-final-fantasy/?page=2 |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |page=2 |date=June 23, 2012 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200929/http://www.gamesradar.com/not-final-fantasy/?page=2 |archive-date=June 2, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Staff for ''[[Complex (website)|Complex]]'', ''[[GameSpot]]'', and ''[[UGO Networks]]'' listed the fight against Giygas as one of the hardest in video games, with the latter and Chloi Rad for ''IGN'' calling him one of the most frightening video game characters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ugo.com/games/giygas | title=Pee Your Pants At The Scariest Characters In Video Games | author=Meli, Marissa | date=June 21, 2011 | publisher=UGO Networks | accessdate=July 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/15-super-hard-classic-game-bosses-who-made-you-yel/2900-24/14/ |title=15 Super Hard Classic Game Bosses Who Made You Yell and Throw Your Controller |work=[[GameSpot]] |date=April 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831202443/https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/15-super-hard-classic-game-bosses-who-made-you-yel/2900-24/14/ |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Littler |first=Chris |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/top-50-hardest-boss-battles?page=3 |title=Top 50 Hardest Boss Battles |work=[[UGO Networks]] |date=August 27, 2010 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902062642/http://www.ugo.com/games/top-50-hardest-boss-battles?page=3 |archive-date=September 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2011/12/the-50-hardest-video-game-bosses-and-how-to-beat-them#39 | title=The 50 Hardest Video Game Bosses (And How To Beat Them) | author=Kalista, Randy | date=December 14, 2011 | work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] | accessdate=July 22, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213100355/http://www.complex.com/video-games/2011/12/the-50-hardest-video-game-bosses-and-how-to-beat-them#39 | archive-date=December 13, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/30/13-of-the-scariest-moments-in-non-horror-games |title=13 of the Scariest Moments in Non-Horror Games |work=[[IGN]] |last=Rad |first=Chloi |date=February 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607014046/https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/30/13-of-the-scariest-moments-in-non-horror-games |archive-date=June 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was featured in a ''[[GameSpot]]'' user-voted poll of the greatest villains in video games, where he lost in the first round to ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'' antagonist [[Darth Malak]].<ref name=\"gs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/greatest-video-game-villain/vote/battle-hub/index.html?battle_id=9 |title=All Time Greatest Game Villain - Darth Malak vs. Giygas |work=[[GameSpot]] |date=September 2010 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109042900/http://www.gamespot.com/greatest-video-game-villain/vote/battle-hub/index.html?battle_id=9 |archive-date=November 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNadia Oxford for ''IGN'' listed the battle with Giygas as one of the most memorable moments in ''EarthBound'' and stated that its significance resonated with people who had not played the game, a sentiment that Cassandra Ramos of ''RPGamer'' shared.<ref>{{cite web |title=Earthbound's Ten Most Memorable Moments |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/07/23/earthbounds-ten-most-memorable-moments |work=[[IGN]] |last=Oxford |first=Nadia |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Qsqyemb6?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/07/23/earthbounds-ten-most-memorable-moments |archive-date=July 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"rpgamer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/features/2013/villains/giygas.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709114520/http://www.rpgamer.com/features/2013/villains/giygas.html |title=Favorite Villains |last=Ramos |first=Cassandra |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archivedate=July 9, 2013}}</ref> In a work for ''1UP.com'', Oxford claimed that Itoi took inspiration from [[Stephen King]] novels, including ''[[It (novel)|It]]''. She suggested that Giygas was based on ''It''{{'}}s antagonist due to a similarly \"borderline indescribable\" form and the fact that they both succumb to \"childlike qualities such as faith, friendship, and love.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Your Mother: Shigesato Itoi |url=http://www.1up.com/features/mother-shigesato-itoi |work=[[1UP.com]] |last=Oxford |first=Nadia |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110131707/http://www.1up.com/features/mother-shigesato-itoi |archive-date=January 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> She discusses how the battle with Giygas in ''Mother'' deviates from traditional final boss battles, citing his deep motivations and music employed, which consists of a \"shrill background noise\" and a lullaby. She suggested that Giygas' degraded form in ''EarthBound'' was possibly the result of Giygas' longing for Maria's love.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spacebound: How Aliens Shape the EarthBound Story |url=http://www.1up.com/features/spacebound-aliens-shape-earthbound-story |work=[[1UP.com]] |last1=Oxford |first1=Nadia |last2=Oxford |first2=David |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110131841/http://www.1up.com/features/spacebound-aliens-shape-earthbound-story |archive-date=January 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Patricia Hernandez for Nightmare Mode discussed how his ''Mother'' incarnation \"echoes a motif\" of children without parental guidance doing poorly for it.<ref name=\"mother\">{{cite web |url=http://nightmaremode.thegamerstrust.com/2012/11/18/childhood-women-and-heterosexuality-a-critique-of-mother/ |title=Labyrinth of Someone Else's Memory: Mother |work=Nightmare Mode |last=Hernandez |first=Patricia |date=November 18, 2012 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607031607/https://nightmaremode.thegamerstrust.com/2012/11/18/childhood-women-and-heterosexuality-a-critique-of-mother/ |archive-date=June 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Colin Snyder for ''[[Vice (website)|Vice]]'' felt similarly, stating that his story is about the loss of childhood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z443ke/the-end-of-the-world-is-a-game |title=The End of the World is a Game |work=[[Vice (website)|Vice]] |last=Snyder |first=Colin |date=December 21, 2012 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720185501/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z443ke/the-end-of-the-world-is-a-game |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> William Hughes for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' argued that Giygas had an [[oedipal complex]] due to his infatuation with his surrogate mother and hatred for his surrogate father over him stealing information from the aliens.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://games.avclub.com/earthbound-s-absent-dad-reveals-its-mother-loving-heart-1798252125 |title=EarthBound\u2019s absent dad reveals its mother-loving heart |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |last=Hughes |first=William |date=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607023417/https://games.avclub.com/earthbound-s-absent-dad-reveals-its-mother-loving-heart-1798252125 |archive-date=June 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{EarthBound series}}\n\n[[Category:Cyborg characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Mother (video game series)]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial supervillains]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo antagonists]]\n[[Category:Telepath characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1989]]\n[[Category:Video game characters who use magic]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n|name = Giygas\n|color = #A00010\n|image =File:Giygas.png\n|caption = Giygas as he appears in ''[[EarthBound]]''\n|series = [[EarthBound (series)|EarthBound]]\n|species = [[Extraterrestrial Life|Alien]]\n|first = ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]'' (1989)\n|last = ''[[EarthBound]]'' (1994)\n|creator = [[Shigesato Itoi]]\n}}\n'''Giygas''', also known as '''Giegue''', and {{nihongo|'''Gyiyg'''|\u30ae\u30fc\u30b0|G\u012bgu}} in Japan, is a [[Extraterrestrials in fiction|fictional alien character]] in the ''[[EarthBound (series)|EarthBound]]'' video game series by [[Nintendo]], created by [[Shigesato Itoi]]. The character serves as the main antagonist of ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]'' and its sequel, ''[[EarthBound]]''. He invades Earth in an attempt to wipe out humanity in ''Mother'', and returns in ''EarthBound'' where he conquers the world and sends his forces into the past to ensure that protagonist [[Ness (EarthBound)|Ness]] could not defeat him. The battle against Giygas, which depicts him in turmoil, drew inspiration from a Japanese film which traumatized Itoi as a child. He has received positive reception with critics referring to his battle as one of the creepiest and most difficult in video games. He has been the subject of analysis and speculation, with an [[urban legend]] being spread about the final battle with him in ''EarthBound'' being a representation of an abortion, which staff denied.\n\n==Concept and creation==\nGiygas was designed and written by the creator of the [[EarthBound (series)|''EarthBound'' series]],  [[Shigesato Itoi]], and debuted in the original ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]''. He is known as Gyiyg in Japanese and Giegue in the canceled English localization. In an interview on his website, Itoi describes how his inspiration for the final battle with Giygas in ''EarthBound'' resulted from a traumatic childhood event where he accidentally viewed the wrong movie at a theater, a [[Shintoho]] film entitled ''[[Kenpei to barabara shibijin]]''. The film featured a murder scene near a river that Itoi mistook for a rape scene which affected him so much that his parents began to worry about his well-being. Years later, Itoi integrated the experience into Giygas' dialogue for the final battle. Itoi described Giygas as something that people cannot make sense of, but also as a living being who deserves love. He described the film scene as a combination of atrocity and eroticism, and that is what his lines are in the end. While designing this battle, Itoi spoke all of the text out loud while another staff member, Matchan Miura, wrote it down. He spoke each [[hiragana]] character one by one because he found it scarier.<ref name = \"Itoi interview\">{{cite interview |first=Itoi |last=Shigesato |url=http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/07.html |title=[Interview with Shigesato Itoi] |work=1101.com |date=April 24, 2003 |language=Japanese |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6QrkuC8iK?url=http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/07.html |archive-date=July 6, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"1101.com\">{{cite interview |last=Shigesato |first=Itoi |title=[Interview with Shigesato Itoi] |url=http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/03.html |language=Japanese |work=1101.com |date=April 18, 2003 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330065450/http://www.1101.com/MOTHER/03.html |archive-date=March 30, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> There has been a misunderstanding regarding the influence of the film on Giygas, with some believing that imagery, dialogue, or audio from that film were used here, when the only thing Itoi took from it was the ability to \"manipulate an audience's emotional state.\"<ref name=\"lol\"/> Music composer [[Hirokazu Tanaka]] described Giygas as the \"embodiment of evil\". As a result, he composed the music in a certain way based on the player's proximity to him. For example, in battles where Ness and company encounter someone or something under Giygas' control, the music and sound effects reflect this.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Hirokazu |first=Tanaka |interviewer=Baiyon |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/26447/Interview_PixelJunk_Edens_Baiyon_Vs_Metroids_Hip_Tanaka.php |title=Interview: ''PixelJunk Eden''{{'}}s Baiyon Vs. ''Metroid''{{'}}s Hip Tanaka |work=[[Gamasutra]] |date=December 14, 2009 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018185959/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/26447/Interview_PixelJunk_Edens_Baiyon_Vs_Metroids_Hip_Tanaka.php |archive-date=October 18, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBefore the release of ''EarthBound'', the localization team had at one point considered localizing Giygas as his original name Giegue or Geek.\"<ref name=\"lol\">{{cite web |url=https://legendsoflocalization.com/earthbound/giygas/ |title=Giygas |work=Legends of Localization |last=Mandelin |first=Clyde |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901012650/https://legendsoflocalization.com/earthbound/giygas/ |archive-date=September 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was speculated that the change from Giegue to Giygas was due to a change in localization staff.<ref name=\"lol\"/> An [[urban legend]] exists that suggests that the final battle with Giygas in ''EarthBound'' was an \"alien [[abortion]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top 7... Creepiest gaming urban legends |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-7-creepiest-gaming-urban-legends/ |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |last=Cooper |first=Hollander |date=November 2, 2012 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221092216/http://gamesradar.com/top-7-creepiest-gaming-urban-legends/ |archive-date=February 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Marcus Lindblom]], a member of the English localization team, acknowledged the urban legend, noting that he appreciated the speculation, but debunked the idea as an official interpretation.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Man Who Wrote Earthbound |url=http://kotaku.com/the-man-who-wrote-earthbound-1188669175 |work=[[Kotaku]] |last=Schreier |first=Jason |date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MtORg2Ew?url=http://kotaku.com/the-man-who-wrote-earthbound-1188669175 |archive-date=January 25, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\nGiygas appears in the [[Family Computer]] video game, ''[[Mother (video game)|Mother]]''.<ref name=\"mother\"/> Giygas was raised by Maria, a woman abducted along with her husband George by Giygas' alien race from Earth in the early 1900s. George studied the aliens' PSI powers without permission and escaped back to Earth. Once he matured, Giygas was tasked by his people to make sure that PSI never spread onto Earth. However, Giygas did not want to betray those who raised him, particularly Maria. In the end, he forced himself to detach from Maria and began preparations for the aliens' invasion. Eighty years later, strange things start happening on Earth. These events are eventually revealed to be the work of Giygas. Maria, now a Queen in a magical world called Magicant, explains everything to the protagonists of ''Mother'' after her memories are restored. When the protagonists encounter Giygas, he explains his motives to them while attacking them with his PSI power. Maria urges protagonist Ninten to sing, which weakens Giygas. Ninten, Ana, and Lloyd sing together, forcing Giygas to surrender and flee.\n\nGiygas also appears in the [[Super NES]] sequel ''[[EarthBound]]''.<ref name=\"1up\"/> Giygas is an unseen villain for most of the story, although he possesses humans, animals, and objects who unknowingly do his bidding. According to a character from the future named Buzz Buzz, Giygas destroys the universe ten years in the future. One of his key minions is Pokey Minch, a former friend of protagonist [[Ness (EarthBound)|Ness]]. At first, Dr. Andonuts (the father of playable character [[Jeff Andonuts|Jeff]]) believes that Giygas is residing deep within the Earth, and transports himself and the party there using a machine called the Phase Distorter. When they arrive, they find that Giygas is attacking from that exact location, but from innumerable years in the past. The only way the protagonists can get to Giygas' time period is to alter the Phase Distorter to transport them back in time. When the group finally reaches Giygas, he initially resembles Ness while in the device called the \"Devil's Machine.\" Porky eventually turns the Devil's Machine off, thereby destroying Giygas' body and mind by releasing his power and driving him mad. At this point, Giygas' words are nondescript and nonsensical. Giygas is eventually destroyed by Paula, who prays to the protagonists' friends and family for help. Her praying eventually reaches the player, and the combined prayers do enough damage to Giygas, killing him.\n\n==Reception==\nSince appearing in ''[[EarthBound]]'', Giygas has received largely positive reception. His role and design was regarded as contrasting with the otherwise lighthearted tone of the rest of ''EarthBound''{{'}}s story by Brittany Vincent for ''[[G4TV]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top Unintentionally Terrifying Games Of All Time |url=http://www.g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/717787/top-unintentionally-terrifying-games-of-all-time/ |work=[[G4TV]] |last=Vincent |first=Brittany |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605122659/http://www.g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/717787/top-unintentionally-terrifying-games-of-all-time/ |archive-date=June 5, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cassandra Ramos for ''RPGamer'' identified him as one of her favorite villains, while ''[[1UP.com]]'' staff listed the battle with Giygas as one of the 25 best boss battles, citing the audio and imagery of Giygas as well as the final portion of the battle.<ref name=\"1up\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=4&cId=3173294 |author=1UP Staff |title=25 of the Most Badass Boss Fights of All Time |work=[[1UP.com]] |date=March 17, 2009 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205030310/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=4&cId=3173294 |archive-date=December 5, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"rpgamer\"/> Jeremy Parish for ''1UP.com'' used the battle as an example of how games subvert expectations, where the protagonists employ prayer instead of their most powerful attacks to win.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jeremy |last=Parish |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3149536 |title=Retronauts 5: Earthbound |work=[[1UP.com]] |date=April 13, 2006 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614121824/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3149536 |archive-date=June 14, 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[IGN]]'' staff included the battle with Giygas in their list of the 10 most cinematic video game moments.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 Cinematic Moments in Games |url=http://me.ign.com/en/feature/15877/10-cinematic-moments-in-games |work=[[IGN]] |date=March 10, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007081019/http://me.ign.com/en/feature/15877/10-cinematic-moments-in-games |archive-date=October 7, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''NGamer UK''  staff listed Giygas as one of the most iconic boss encounters in Nintendo history, stating that the defining moment was his design and the method of defeating him.<ref>{{cite web |author=NGamer UK |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendos-most-iconic-boss-encounters/?page=2 |title=Nintendo's most iconic Boss encounters |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=May 11, 2010 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602201131/http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendos-most-iconic-boss-encounters/?page=2 |archive-date=June 2, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' staff named him one of the best video game antagonists, finding him creepy and a more imposing villain than [[Kefka Palazzo]] from ''[[Final Fantasy VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/|title=100 best villains in video games |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=May 17, 2013|accessdate=June 21, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130624192529/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-100-villains-video-games/|archive-date=June 24, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Not Final Fantasy |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/not-final-fantasy/?page=2 |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |page=2 |date=June 23, 2012 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200929/http://www.gamesradar.com/not-final-fantasy/?page=2 |archive-date=June 2, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Staff for ''[[Complex (website)|Complex]]'', ''[[GameSpot]]'', and ''[[UGO Networks]]'' listed the fight against Giygas as one of the hardest in video games, with the latter and Chloi Rad for ''IGN'' calling him one of the most frightening video game characters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ugo.com/games/giygas | title=Pee Your Pants At The Scariest Characters In Video Games | author=Meli, Marissa | date=June 21, 2011 | publisher=UGO Networks | accessdate=July 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/15-super-hard-classic-game-bosses-who-made-you-yel/2900-24/14/ |title=15 Super Hard Classic Game Bosses Who Made You Yell and Throw Your Controller |work=[[GameSpot]] |date=April 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831202443/https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/15-super-hard-classic-game-bosses-who-made-you-yel/2900-24/14/ |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Littler |first=Chris |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/top-50-hardest-boss-battles?page=3 |title=Top 50 Hardest Boss Battles |work=[[UGO Networks]] |date=August 27, 2010 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902062642/http://www.ugo.com/games/top-50-hardest-boss-battles?page=3 |archive-date=September 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2011/12/the-50-hardest-video-game-bosses-and-how-to-beat-them#39 | title=The 50 Hardest Video Game Bosses (And How To Beat Them) | author=Kalista, Randy | date=December 14, 2011 | work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] | accessdate=July 22, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213100355/http://www.complex.com/video-games/2011/12/the-50-hardest-video-game-bosses-and-how-to-beat-them#39 | archive-date=December 13, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/30/13-of-the-scariest-moments-in-non-horror-games |title=13 of the Scariest Moments in Non-Horror Games |work=[[IGN]] |last=Rad |first=Chloi |date=February 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607014046/https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/30/13-of-the-scariest-moments-in-non-horror-games |archive-date=June 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was featured in a ''[[GameSpot]]'' user-voted poll of the greatest villains in video games, where he lost in the first round to ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'' antagonist [[Darth Malak]].<ref name=\"gs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/greatest-video-game-villain/vote/battle-hub/index.html?battle_id=9 |title=All Time Greatest Game Villain - Darth Malak vs. Giygas |work=[[GameSpot]] |date=September 2010 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109042900/http://www.gamespot.com/greatest-video-game-villain/vote/battle-hub/index.html?battle_id=9 |archive-date=November 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNadia Oxford for ''IGN'' listed the battle with Giygas as one of the most memorable moments in ''EarthBound'' and stated that its significance resonated with people who had not played the game, a sentiment that Cassandra Ramos of ''RPGamer'' shared.<ref>{{cite web |title=Earthbound's Ten Most Memorable Moments |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/07/23/earthbounds-ten-most-memorable-moments |work=[[IGN]] |last=Oxford |first=Nadia |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Qsqyemb6?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/07/23/earthbounds-ten-most-memorable-moments |archive-date=July 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"rpgamer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/features/2013/villains/giygas.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709114520/http://www.rpgamer.com/features/2013/villains/giygas.html |title=Favorite Villains |last=Ramos |first=Cassandra |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archivedate=July 9, 2013}}</ref> In a work for ''1UP.com'', Oxford claimed that Itoi took inspiration from [[Stephen King]] novels, including ''[[It (novel)|It]]''. She suggested that Giygas was based on ''It''{{'}}s antagonist due to a similarly \"borderline indescribable\" form and the fact that they both succumb to \"childlike qualities such as faith, friendship, and love.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Your Mother: Shigesato Itoi |url=http://www.1up.com/features/mother-shigesato-itoi |work=[[1UP.com]] |last=Oxford |first=Nadia |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110131707/http://www.1up.com/features/mother-shigesato-itoi |archive-date=January 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> She discusses how the battle with Giygas in ''Mother'' deviates from traditional final boss battles, citing his deep motivations and music employed, which consists of a \"shrill background noise\" and a lullaby. She suggested that Giygas' degraded form in ''EarthBound'' was possibly the result of Giygas' longing for Maria's love.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spacebound: How Aliens Shape the EarthBound Story |url=http://www.1up.com/features/spacebound-aliens-shape-earthbound-story |work=[[1UP.com]] |last1=Oxford |first1=Nadia |last2=Oxford |first2=David |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110131841/http://www.1up.com/features/spacebound-aliens-shape-earthbound-story |archive-date=January 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Patricia Hernandez for Nightmare Mode discussed how his ''Mother'' incarnation \"echoes a motif\" of children without parental guidance doing poorly for it.<ref name=\"mother\">{{cite web |url=http://nightmaremode.thegamerstrust.com/2012/11/18/childhood-women-and-heterosexuality-a-critique-of-mother/ |title=Labyrinth of Someone Else's Memory: Mother |work=Nightmare Mode |last=Hernandez |first=Patricia |date=November 18, 2012 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607031607/https://nightmaremode.thegamerstrust.com/2012/11/18/childhood-women-and-heterosexuality-a-critique-of-mother/ |archive-date=June 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Colin Snyder for ''[[Vice (website)|Vice]]'' felt similarly, stating that his story is about the loss of childhood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z443ke/the-end-of-the-world-is-a-game |title=The End of the World is a Game |work=[[Vice (website)|Vice]] |last=Snyder |first=Colin |date=December 21, 2012 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720185501/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/z443ke/the-end-of-the-world-is-a-game |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> William Hughes for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' argued that Giygas had an [[oedipal complex]] due to his infatuation with his surrogate mother and hatred for his surrogate father over him stealing information from the aliens.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://games.avclub.com/earthbound-s-absent-dad-reveals-its-mother-loving-heart-1798252125 |title=EarthBound\u2019s absent dad reveals its mother-loving heart |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |last=Hughes |first=William |date=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607023417/https://games.avclub.com/earthbound-s-absent-dad-reveals-its-mother-loving-heart-1798252125 |archive-date=June 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{EarthBound series}}\n\n[[Category:Cyborg characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Mother (video game series)]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial supervillains]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo antagonists]]\n[[Category:Telepath characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1989]]\n[[Category:Video game characters who use magic]]\n", "name_user": "QuestingCoconut", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAppearances:corrected character name Porky to Pokey", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giygas"}
